{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567586"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:04:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:04:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19152"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19152"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.21,0.03,0.47,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11886"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102126"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11886"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19152"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84583"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1692"},{"type":"tags","id":"4555"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27849"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28135"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28136"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35544"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102126"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after sustaining a laceration to his right forearm one hour earlier. The cut was from a piece of broken glass whilst washing dishes. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has no known allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a superficial 3 cm linear laceration on the volar aspect of his right forearm. The wound edges are clean and well-approximated. There is no tendon nor deep tissue involvement, and he has normal sensation and movement of his hand and fingers. The wound is not under tension when his wrist is in the neutral position.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate method of wound closure?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Conservative management with dressings","Tissue adhesive","Staples","Simple interrupted sutures","Horizontal mattress sutures"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a superficial laceration that requires consideration of various wound closure techniques. The ideal method should provide good cosmetic outcome while being appropriate for the wound characteristics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETissue adhesive\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice for this wound. It is ideal for clean, linear lacerations less than 5 cm in length that are not under tension. Benefits include quick application, no need for local anaesthetic, and good cosmetic results. The location on the forearm is suitable as it is not in a high-mobility area.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConservative management with dressings\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be inappropriate as this wound requires primary closure for optimal healing and cosmetic outcome. This approach is better suited for heavily contaminated wounds or those requiring delayed primary closure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStaples\u003C/strong\u003E are rapid and effective for scalp wounds but are not ideal for forearm wounds. They tend to leave more noticeable scarring and are better suited for areas covered by hair. They would be particularly inappropriate for areas where cosmetic outcome is important, such as the face.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimple interrupted sutures\u003C/strong\u003E would be effective but are unnecessarily invasive for this simple wound. While they provide excellent wound edge approximation, the characteristics of this wound (clean, linear, minimal tension) make tissue adhesive a better choice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHorizontal mattress sutures\u003C/strong\u003E are typically reserved for wounds under higher tension or those requiring eversion of the edges. They would be excessive for this straightforward laceration and may leave more prominent suture marks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen selecting a wound closure method, key considerations include the wound location, length, depth, tension, and level of contamination. Patient factors such as risk of poor healing (diabetes, steroids) and cosmetic concerns should also be considered.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tissue adhesive is appropriate for superficial lacerations under minimal tension that are less than 5cm in length.","Staples are quick and effective for scalp wounds but should be avoided on the face.","Simple interrupted sutures are versatile and appropriate for most wounds requiring closure."],"references":["Otterness et al. Methods of laceration closure in the ED: A national perspective. The American Journal of Emergency Medicine. 2020. https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0735675719304954"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84583"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19152"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84583"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-08T14:51:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-08T14:52:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11886"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102126"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"